{{Football club infobox | clubname = Etoile Haïtienne | image = | image_size = | fullname = Etoile Haïtienne | nickname = | founded = {{Start date and age|1936}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZF8NAAAAYAAJ&q=etoile+haitienne+football&dq=etoile+haitienne+football&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjrn9Tqh_7SAhWJ7yYKHd6pD9cQ6AEIGjAA |title=Le football haïtien à travers les âges: 1900-1977 |author=Chauvel, Louis |page=15 |publisher=Impr. H. Deschamps |accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> | ground = | capacity = | chairman = | manager = | league = Championnat National D3<ref name="RSSSF_2003"/> | season = 2003 | position = Championnat National D2 (relegated) }}
'''Etoile Haïtienne''' ({{IPA-fr|e.twal ajisjɛ̃n}}, [[English language|English]]: ''Haitian Star'') is a professional [[Association football|football]] club based in [[Port-au-Prince]], [[Haiti]].<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/tablesh/haitichamp.html RSSSF: Haiti – List of Champions] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304024733/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesh/haitichamp.html |date=March 4, 2016 }}</ref><ref name="Hall">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3RbzX4PjxtgC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Historical Dictionary of Haiti |editor=Hall, Michael R. |page=117 |year=2012 |isbn=9780810878105 |accessdate=2 April 2016}}</ref> After the 2003 season, the club was relegated to Division 3.<ref name="RSSSF_2003">[http://www.rsssf.com/tablesh/haiti2010.html RSSSF - Haiti 2003]</ref>
The last ''known'' time the club played in Division 1 was in 1970.<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/tablesh/haiti70.html RSSSF: 1970 Haiti]</ref>
==History== Etoile Haïtienne appeared in its first championship in 1942 against longer established [[Racing Club Haïtien]], another club in [[Port-au-Prince]].{{refn|group=note|According to the Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation, rsssf.com, cup matches were played throughout the country, but the national championships were restricted to top-level clubs from Port-au-Prince only, and a few surrounding areas within. It wasn't until 1988, that the national championship was fully integrated in to league format outside of the capital.<ref>{{cite web|title=Haiti – List of Champions |publisher=RSSSF |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesh/haitichamp.html |accessdate=17 April 2016 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304024733/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesh/haitichamp.html |archivedate=March 4, 2016 }}</ref>}} Down 3–0 at halftime and less than ten minutes after Racing's last goal, [[Joe Gaetjens]] rebounded and scored to break the shutout. At the 53rd minute, Fritz Joseph scores. Seven minutes remaining, Frérot Rouzier scores the tying goal equalizing the match at 3–3. At the final minutes of regulation, a defiant Gaetjens kept on the attack, breaking the tie at 3–4, which ended up being the game-winner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LVbRAQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=The Shot Heard Around the World: The Joe Gaetjens Story |author=Gaetjens, Lesly |pages=1, 3–4, 16, 24 |year=2010 |isbn=9780557612314 |accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref><ref name="1942/43">[http://www.rsssf.com/tablesh/haiti43.html RSSSF – Haiti 1942/43]</ref> To this day, Racing Club Haïtien refuses to play matches on the "[[Maundy Thursday|Jeudi Saint]]" (''Holy Thursday''); the day of ''washing of the feet.''<ref name="1942/43"/>
==Honours== *'''[[Ligue Haïtienne]]: 3''' :: 1942, 1944, 1961
==International competitions== *'''[[CONCACAF Champions League]]: 1 appearance''' ::[[1962 CONCACAF Champions' Cup|1962]] – First Round – Lost against {{flagicon|ANT}} [[RKV FC SITHOC|SITHOC]], 3–8 on aggregate (3–2, 0–6)
